The people of Macedonia vote in a referendum on whether to change the name of the country;
The Macedonian people voted in a referendum on Sunday on whether to change its name to "the Republic of North Macedonia," a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked its membership bids for the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbor in its north represents a possibility of ownership of its territory and vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change weakens the ethnic identity of Macedonia's Slav majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether participation will reach the minimum of 50 percent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum vote reads: "You are in favour of membership in NATO and in the EU by accepting the agreement with Greece."
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a reasonable consequence for Macedonia to enter bodies such as the EU and NATO, one of the countries emerging from the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I came today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union because it means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
Although not legally binding, enough members of parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said there were no reports of irregularities as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016 when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
"I came to vote because of my children, our place is in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian PM Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko voted for the referendum in Macedonia on changing the country's name giving him the opportunity to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was assembling a small stage and preparing seats in front of the tents armed by those who would make a boycott of the referendum.
"We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we must proudly enter under our own conditions, not by commanding others," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don't accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and be part of Euro-Asian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev says membership in NATO will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I believe the vast majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after voting.
He said that a result in favour of changing the name would be "confirmation of our future."
A survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Policy Research Institute said that between 30 and 43 percent of voters will take part in the referendum - an amount below that of the required participation.
Another poll, conducted by Macedonian Telma TV, found that 57 percent of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
In order for the referendum to be successful, the turnout must be 50 percent and one more vote.
