John Edward: Essential language skills for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which is only bolstered with individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, for their chosen career and for their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages remain a topic of popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If a man speaks in a language that he understands, he understands with his mind.
If he speaks in his own language, he understands with his own heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent examinations, we can see that languages are leading in the ranking tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a Higher A grade.
The data, collected from the 74 schools that are members of the SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a Higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who study German, 69 percent of those who study French and 63 percent who study Spanish also achieved A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages are now, as a choice of subject, being kept in the same regard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that out of reasons given by employers for struggling to fill vacancies, 17 per cent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more imperative in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you learn another language, it will have a real advantage in the future as it will have the ability to last a lifetime like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual person at the forefront of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation and, with 15 percent, French is the only language spoken with a two-digit percentage.
That's why investing in language learning is now important for today's children.
Knowing more than one language, particularly those of developing economies, children will have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will learn different languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at present, in a global business environment, that languages remain very important for the future of the country, and therefore this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's the fair of the fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
