North Korea says 'in no way' it will unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening its mistrust of the United States and that there was no way the country would unilaterally leave its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "considerable good will measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any trust in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will in no way unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri repeated familiar complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement appeared to be significant that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without thought as Pyong had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work towards "the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump vowed to "denuclearize the Korean peninsula."
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to reduce tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal coherently, and even objects to the 'declaration of an end to the war,'" said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can break us is a dream of people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our lack of confidence."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party to this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to this block."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the U.S. mainland with North Korean rockets was inevitable after "Mr. Cathy President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on missiles.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much work remained to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timeline for this, saying "If it takes two years, three years or five months - it makes no difference."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, Thursday, told the U.N. Security Council that: "Enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without stalling until we realize fully and finally verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions on North Korea since 2006 with the aim of halting funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri in the margins of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, after North Korea in a few hours criticized him for making "gangster-like demands".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "corresponding measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on taking enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has managed to get all of its undergraduate students to sleep more with the aim of fighting the growing macho culture of studying all night and staying awake thanks to caffeine.
An academic has found that university students in the first place in the world often don't have an idea about the basic real things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after making a speech about the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
Finally a girl came over to me and said, "Why are you telling me this now, in my last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which started for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials about how good sleep traditions help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students had serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to capture the effects of caffeine and light and on how athletic performance has an effect from a sleep deficit, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, di-stress and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it's not going to change students' behavior right away.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as much as you have a right to know the health effects when choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of being proud that "you managed to stay up all night studying" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that he gets enough sleep, and of good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, severe fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, since lack of sleep puts the mind in a hungry mode, making them hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California, studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to insist on a course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to make a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students should consider making an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as for when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can unbalance your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble sleeping.
