In 1996, a tsunami also struck the western side of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is often hit by earthquakes.
These are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a large earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in the north of Sumatra triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast with great force, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake strikes near the city of Padang, the capital of the western province of Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck one of the Mentawai islands, off Sumatra, triggering a 10-metre-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, causing devastation and panic as people remembered the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
